Yes! That is actually a much better approach and it makes business sense.

Instead of:

🟦 Achieved

⬜ Remaining


you want:

🔵 Actual

🟣 Forecast

🟦 Remaining Budget


So the donut becomes:

Budget = Actual + Forecast + Remaining Budget

This means the three slices always add up to 100% of the Budget.

Example 1 (Negative Variance)

Budget = 172.6K

Actual = 70K

Forecast = 71.3K

Total Actual + Forecast = 141.3K

Remaining Budget:

172.6 − 141.3 = 31.3K

The donut becomes:

🔵 Actual = 70K

🟣 Forecast = 71.3K

🟦 Remaining Budget = 31.3K


The center shows:

-18%
vs Budget

This tells the user:

> We have achieved 141.3K and still need 31.3K to reach the budget.




---

Example 2 (Positive Variance)

Budget = 100K

Actual = 60K

Forecast = 50K

Actual + Forecast = 110K

Remaining Budget:

100 − 110 = -10K

Since Remaining Budget cannot be negative:

Remaining Budget = 0

The donut becomes:

🔵 Actual = 60K

🟣 Forecast = 50K

🟦 Remaining Budget = 0


The center shows:

+10%
vs Budget


---

DAX Measures

Actual

Actual Slice =
[Actual 2026]


---

Forecast

Forecast Slice =
[Forecast 2026]


---

Remaining Budget

Remaining Budget Slice =
MAX(
    [Budget 2026] - [Actual 2026] - [Forecast 2026],
    0
)

The MAX(..., 0) ensures that if Actual + Forecast exceeds Budget, the remaining slice becomes 0 instead of a negative value.


---

Create the category table

Donut Category =
DATATABLE(
    "Category", STRING,
    {
        {"Actual"},
        {"Forecast"},
        {"Remaining"}
    }
)


---

Create the donut value measure

Donut Value =
SWITCH(
    SELECTEDVALUE('Donut Category'[Category]),
    "Actual", [Actual Slice],
    "Forecast", [Forecast Slice],
    "Remaining", [Remaining Budget Slice]
)


---

Use in the Donut Chart

Legend

Donut Category[Category]

Values

Donut Value

Colors

🔵 Actual → Dark Blue

🟣 Forecast → Purple

🟦 Remaining Budget → Cyan


This approach gives you a donut where:

Actual and Forecast are shown as separate achieved portions.

The third slice represents only the budget that is still left to achieve.

If you exceed the budget, the remaining slice disappears.

The center KPI (Variance %) still shows the percentage above or below budget. This is a clear business representation and works well with slicers.
